Namaste Rahul and others,

  We all have some fire within us. When we chann=
el it properly, we fulfil our dharma successfully. When the fire is unchann=
eled and beset with impurities, we waste energy and fail to fulfil our dhar=
ma.

  Fire in conjunction with sattwa guna generates knowledge (jnaana sha=
kti). Fire in conjunction with rajo guna generates actions (kriyaa shakti).=
 Fire in conjunction with tamo guna generates desires (ichchhaa shakti). We=
 need people who mainly have sattwa and also some rajas. Such people have c=
lear thinking backed by correct knowledge and engage in fruitful actions. I=
t is more important to engage in a few fruitful actions than to engage in t=
oo many mis-directed actions and be left with unfulfilled desires and frust=
ration, which is what happens when there is too much tamas and rajas. There=
 are many self-styled "Hindutva" warriors today who fall in the latter cate=
gory. They yell from rooftops in shrill voices, but do not accomplish much.=
 Do we need some more such people?

  *        *        *

  What Hindutva =
needs today is a few detached Arjunas who destroy mighty armies without hat=
red for anyone in their heart. What Hindutva needs today is a few detached =
Vivekanandas who inspire millions with their magnetic personality without a=
ny passion in their heart.

  Act like a passionate man, but have no passio=
n in your heart. Fight unwaveringly, but have no hatred for anyone.

  If o=
ne is fighting a war with passion, frustration or hatred in one's heart, on=
e will only go so far and achieve only so much. What such a person achieves=
 will be short-lived. If one first overcomes attractions and repulsions, ha=
s a stable and unperturbed heart without passion and hatred and becomes a d=
etached instrument of Nature engaging in spontaneous actions without any at=
tachment, one will achieve much more and what one achieves will be long-liv=
ed.

  I am writing this to this group of people because my intuition tells=
 me that there are some on this group who have the potential to become such=
 instruments of Mother.

  Do some spiritual sadhana first and overcome the=
 weaknesses. Have a stable, unperturbed and equanimous heart. Then Nature w=
ill show you the way.

  *        *        *

  Ceturies ago, western invad=
ers went about their business with great dexterity and patience to affect t=
he psyche of Hindus, especially intelligentsia. Their slow, patient, dexter=
ous and systematic propaganda is bearing fruit even today. To undo their wo=
rk, one needs to be equally dexterous and patient. This is not the work for=
 hot-blooded, angry and frustrated people. One needs to be cool-headed, sma=
rt and patient.

  Another thing is that sanatana dharma is broken today. I=
n pursuit of modern education, the cream of Indian intelligentsia stopped e=
ngaging in our traditional knowledge. This brought a discontinuity in knowl=
edge. We have some faithful Hindus engaging in superstitious and/or purpose=
less practices. We have many priests who are corrupted by money and fame, d=
on't do any sadhana and don't have any spiritual strength. Many intelligent=
 people either dissociate themselves from religion or follow religion passi=
vely without much faith and with some shame or misgivings. At the root of t=
his is the broken knowledge and purposeless practices.

  Also, we have man=
y bad practices that afflict Hinduism due to Kali, which need to be gotten =
rid of. For example, caste system of today is so different from old days. T=
he concept of caste mobility is gone now - one would start with father's ca=
ste, but get a caste later on based on one's aptitude and attitude in old d=
ays. For example, Valmiki was a shudra by birth who lived by killing birds =
and he became a brahmana and a brahmarshi later. Vishwamitra was a kshatriy=
a by birth but became a brahmana and a brahmarshi later and even became one=
 of saptarshis. If lower caste and untouchable Hindus feel aversion to Hind=
uism which is exploted by Christian missionaries who offer money and respec=
t to convert, some fault lies with Hinduism too. We need to reform casteism=
.

  There are many things that need to be done. At one level, some propaga=
nda needs to be done on the greatness of Hinduism. This needs to be done wi=
th a cool, scholarly and patient attitude (as opposed to yelling in shrill =
voice from rooftops like some Hindutva activists foolishly do). At another =
level, broken links within Hinduism need to be rediscovered so that the kno=
wledgebase of our philosophy is correctly represented to sway the intellige=
ntsia. While other religions are based on "faith" in the words of a messiah=
, Hinduism has a wide-ranging and sophisticated philosophy and methods that=
 can enable anyone to become a messiah. However, the knowledge has become c=
orrupted and incomplete and some intelligent people are justified in not ha=
ving faith. At yet another level, we need to reform some social and cultura=
l aspects of Hindusm and undo some changes brought in by Kali.

  There are=
 many things to do and this will take many decades of focused and concerted=
 effort.

  *        *        *

  Personally, I have no doubt that the tim=
e of weakening (or even fall) of certain faiths has come. In the next few d=
ecades, some faiths will be weakened considerably and sanatana dharma will =
be strengthened. However, this being Kali yuga, such a change will not be p=
ermanent.

